docs.abstract: When driving through Natchez, Miss., it is easy to overlook Forks of the Road. But from 1833 to 1863, it was among the largest slave markets in America.
docs.snippet: When driving through Natchez, Miss., it is easy to overlook Forks of the Road. But from 1833 to 1863, it was among the largest slave markets in America.
docs.lead_paragraph: NATCHEZ, Miss. — When driving through Natchez, Miss., a town popular with tourists, it is easy to overlook an awkwardly shaped patch of land, only modestly marked by a few signs, free-standing exhibits and shackles cemented in the ground.

headline.main: How a Slave Market Became a National Park Service Site

docs.abstract: The Miami restaurant’s long history for protesters and revelers continues, with recent demonstrations denouncing shortages of food and medicine in Cuba.
docs.snippet: The Miami restaurant’s long history for protesters and revelers continues, with recent demonstrations denouncing shortages of food and medicine in Cuba.
docs.lead_paragraph: MIAMI — Outside Versailles Restaurant, on Calle Ocho, near Miami’s Little Havana, thousands of protesters have gathered in the last two weeks, waving red, white and blue flags — Cuban and American — in the pouring rain and the suffocating humidity.

headline.main: For Decades, Versailles Restaurant Has Been a Hub for Cuban Protests
headline.print_headline: A Hub for Food and More

docs.abstract: The stunning rise of England’s soccer team is helping define a new vision of Englishness, putting the lie to those who would stir culture wars.
docs.snippet: The stunning rise of England’s soccer team is helping define a new vision of Englishness, putting the lie to those who would stir culture wars.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — Lee Anderson will not be watching the match. He has not seen so much as a minute of England’s progress through this summer’s European soccer championship. He missed the drab, underwhelming early games, the thrilling, cathartic victory against Germany, the smooth dismissal of Ukraine and the gripping, tortuous defeat of Denmark.

headline.main: Soccer Success Is Making England ‘Whole Again’

docs.abstract: The tennis superstar is guest-editing Racquet magazine and has written a cover essay for Time. What’s left for traditional sports journalism?
docs.snippet: The tennis superstar is guest-editing Racquet magazine and has written a cover essay for Time. What’s left for traditional sports journalism?
docs.lead_paragraph: In early May, a couple of weeks before she tweeted that she wouldn’t appear at a required news conference at the French Open, Naomi Osaka was on a Zoom call with a writer for Racquet magazine who was trying to gain insight into the athlete’s inner life.

headline.main: Naomi Osaka Is Talking to the Media Again, but on Her Own Terms
headline.print_headline: Tennis Star Shows Power Shift in Sports Journalism

docs.abstract: A video of a violent arrest raised questions about balancing a push to enforce laws in the subway against concerns about police abuses.
docs.snippet: A video of a violent arrest raised questions about balancing a push to enforce laws in the subway against concerns about police abuses.
docs.lead_paragraph: A video of police officers swarming a subway rider and shooting him with a Taser this month has revived a contentious debate about policing on New York’s public transit system, even as the person likely to lead the city has made subway safety a top priority.

headline.main: He Paid His Subway Fare. Then He Was Tasered by the Police.
headline.print_headline: He Paid His Own Fare.  Then He Was Tasered And Arrested by Police.

docs.abstract: The death of Lindani Myeni became a cause célèbre in South Africa, intensifying criticism there of racism in the United States and a feeling of solidarity with African Americans.
docs.snippet: The death of Lindani Myeni became a cause célèbre in South Africa, intensifying criticism there of racism in the United States and a feeling of solidarity with African Americans.
docs.lead_paragraph: Three Honolulu police officers will not face criminal charges in the fatal shooting of a South African rugby player whose death became a cause célèbre in South Africa and intensified criticism there of police killings of Black people in the United States, prosecutors said this week.

headline.main: No Charges for Honolulu Police Officers Who Fatally Shot South African Man

docs.abstract: Two officers engaged in “shocking professional and sexual misconduct” with a 15-year-old, a disciplinary trial judge wrote, but they have not been criminally charged.
docs.snippet: Two officers engaged in “shocking professional and sexual misconduct” with a 15-year-old, a disciplinary trial judge wrote, but they have not been criminally charged.
docs.lead_paragraph: Two New York Police Department officers were fired this year after a disciplinary trial judge wrote that they had engaged in “shocking professional and sexual misconduct” with a teenage girl who was a member of one of the department’s youth programs, departmental records show.

headline.main: Officer Fired After N.Y.P.D. Finds He Raped Girl From Youth Program
headline.print_headline: 2 N.Y.P.D. Officers Fired For Sexual Abuse of Girl

docs.abstract: The church’s official positions do not line up neatly with progressive or conservative opinion.
docs.snippet: The church’s official positions do not line up neatly with progressive or conservative opinion.
docs.lead_paragraph: A social historian looking for a defense of the Black Power movement in popular magazines and newspapers of the 1960s would have to do a great deal of digging. Such an inquirer would have an easier time quarrying the pages of Triumph, a little-remembered Catholic periodical started by L. Brent Bozell, a brother-in-law of William F. Buckley Jr., the founder of National Review.

headline.main: This Is Why America Needs Catholicism

docs.abstract: Tourists, particularly Black travelers, are paying close attention to how destinations and travel service providers approach diversity and equity after a year of social justice protests.
docs.snippet: Tourists, particularly Black travelers, are paying close attention to how destinations and travel service providers approach diversity and equity after a year of social justice protests.
docs.lead_paragraph: Between the Covid-19 pandemic, which brought tourism to a near-complete halt for months on end, and last summer’s protests for social justice, the past year has been one of reckoning for the travel industry on issues of race and inclusivity.

headline.main: The Travel Industry’s Reckoning With Race and Inclusion
headline.print_headline: The Travel Sector Is Having a Reckoning With Race
